# Angular & Typescript Standards

This document defines the Angular and Typescript coding standards, all code must follow these patterns and conventions

## Modern Angular Patterns (Required)

### Standalone Components

**All new components must be standalone** (no NgModules)

- **Never** declare components in NgModules
- Import specific dependencies, not barrel modules
- Keep imports list minimal and explicit

```typescript
// ✅ DO: Standalone component with explicit imports
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { RouterLink } from '@angular/router';
import { NgOptimizedImage } from '@angular/common';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-header',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [RouterLink, NgOptimizedImage],
  templateUrl: './header.component.html',
})
export class HeaderComponent {}

// ❌ DON'T: Declaring in an NgModule
@NgModule({
  declarations: [HeaderComponent],
  imports: [CommonModule, RouterModule],
})
export class HeaderModule {}
```

### Control Flow Syntax

**Use modern control flow** (`@if`, `@for`, `@switch`) instead of structural directives

**Requirements:**

- Always include `track` expression in `@for`
- Use `track item.id` or `track $index` for primitive arrays
- No `*ngIf`, `ngFor`, `ngSwitch` in new code

```html
<!-- ✅ DO: Modern control flow -->
@if (user()) {
<p>Welcome, {{ user().name }}</p>
} @else {
<p>Please log in.</p>
} @for (item of items(); track item.id) {
<li>{{ item.label }}</li>
} @switch (status()) { @case ('active') { <span>Active</span> } @case ('inactive') {
<span>Inactive</span> } @default { <span>Unknown</span> } }

<!-- ❌ DON'T: Structural directives -->
<p *ngIf="user">Welcome</p>
<li *ngFor="let item of items">{{ item.label }}</li>
<span [ngSwitch]="status">...</span>
```

### Signals (Preferred State Management)

**Use signals for reactive state** instead of traditional observables when possible:

**Signal Guidelines:**

- Use `signal()` for mutable reactive state
- Use `computed()` for derived values
- Use `effect()` for side effects (logging, localStorage, etc.)
- Call signals with `()` to read values
- Use `.set()` to replace, `.update()` to transform
- Signals are synchronus - no async/await needed

```typescript
import { Component, signal, computed, effect } from '@angular/core';

@Component({ ... })
export class CounterComponent {
  // ✅ DO: signal() for mutable state
  count = signal(0);

  // ✅ DO: computed() for derived values
  doubled = computed(() => this.count() * 2);

  constructor() {
    // ✅ DO: effect() for side effects
    effect(() => {
      localStorage.setItem('count', String(this.count()));
    });
  }

  increment(): void {
    // ✅ DO: .update() to transform based on current value
    this.count.update(c => c + 1);
  }

  reset(): void {
    // ✅ DO: .set() to replace the value
    this.count.set(0);
  }
}
```

### ViewChild Pattern with Signals and Effect

**PREFERRED**: Use signal-based `viewChild()` instead of `@ViewChild` decorator, and react to template availability using `effect()` instead of `ngAfterViewInit`.

```typescript
import { Component, viewChild, ElementRef, effect } from '@angular/core';

@Component({ ... })
export class ChartComponent {
  // ✅ DO: signal-based viewChild()
  private canvas = viewChild<ElementRef<HTMLCanvasElement>>('canvas');

  constructor() {
    effect(() => {
      const el = this.canvas();
      if (el) {
        // Runs whenever canvas becomes available
        this.initChart(el.nativeElement);
      }
    });
  }

  // ❌ DON'T: @ViewChild decorator + ngAfterViewInit
  // @ViewChild('canvas') canvas!: ElementRef<HTMLCanvasElement>;
  // ngAfterViewInit() { this.initChart(this.canvas.nativeElement); }
}
```

### Input/Output Properties

**Use signal-based input()/output()** instead of decorators

```typescript
import { Component, input, output } from '@angular/core';

@Component({ ... })
export class ButtonComponent {
  // ✅ DO: signal-based inputs
  label = input.required<string>();
  disabled = input(false);

  // ✅ DO: signal-based output
  clicked = output<void>();

  handleClick(): void {
    this.clicked.emit();
  }
}

// ❌ DON'T: decorator-based inputs/outputs
// @Input() label!: string;
// @Output() clicked = new EventEmitter<void>();
```

```html
<!-- Usage in template — same as before -->
<app-button [label]="'Submit'" (clicked)="onSubmit()" />
```

### Dependacy Injection

**Both `inject()` and contructor injection are acceptable**

```typescript
import { Component, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { UserService } from './user.service';

// ✅ DO: inject() function (preferred for new code)
@Component({ ... })
export class ProfileComponent {
  private userService = inject(UserService);
}

// ✅ ALSO OK: constructor injection
@Component({ ... })
export class ProfileComponent {
  constructor(private userService: UserService) {}
}
```

### Change Detection

**Always use OnPush change detection**

```typescript
import { Component, ChangeDetectionStrategy } from '@angular/core';

// ✅ DO: OnPush on every component
@Component({
  selector: 'app-card',
  standalone: true,
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  templateUrl: './card.component.html',
})
export class CardComponent {}

// ❌ DON'T: Default change detection (omitting changeDetection)
@Component({
  selector: 'app-card',
  standalone: true,
  templateUrl: './card.component.html',
})
export class CardComponent {}
```

### Class/Style Bindings

**Use direct bindings** instead of `ngClass`/`ngStyle`

```html
<!-- ✅ DO: Direct class and style bindings -->
<button [class.active]="isActive()" [class.disabled]="isDisabled()">Click</button>
<p [style.color]="textColor()" [style.font-size.px]="fontSize()">Hello</p>

<!-- ✅ DO: class binding with an object expression for multiple classes -->
<div [class]="{ active: isActive(), hidden: !isVisible() }">Content</div>

<!-- ❌ DON'T: ngClass / ngStyle -->
<button [ngClass]="{ active: isActive(), disabled: isDisabled() }">Click</button>
<p [ngStyle]="{ color: textColor(), fontSize: fontSize() + 'px' }">Hello</p>
```

### Template Restictions

**No arrow functions or complex logic in templates**

```html
<!-- ✅ DO: call a method defined on the component class -->
<button (click)="handleSave()">Save</button>
<p>{{ formatDate(event().date) }}</p>

<!-- ❌ DON'T: arrow functions or inline logic in templates -->
<button (click)="() => save(item)">Save</button>
<p>{{ items().filter(i => i.active).length }}</p>
```

```typescript
// ✅ DO: move logic into the component
export class EventComponent {
  handleSave(): void {
    /* ... */
  }
  formatDate(date: Date): string {
    return date.toLocaleDateString();
  }
}
```

